<h1 class="text-center">Ray Bradbury</h1>
<h2 class="text-center"><em>American science fiction novelist, short story writer, essayist, playwright, screenwriter and poet whose works were translated in more than 40 languages and sold millions of copies around the world.</em></h2>
<div class="thumbnail"><img class="smaller-image" src="http://cdn8.openculture.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/ray-bradbury-zen.jpg" alt="Ray Bradbury"></div>
<div>
  <h3><strong> Here's a time line of Ray Bradbury's life:</strong></h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>August 22, 1920</strong> Borned in Waukegan, Illinois to Esther Bradbury a Swedish immigrant and Leonard Spaulding Bradbury a power and telephone lineman of English Descent</li>
<li><strong>1931</strong> At age eleven, young Ray began writing his own stories</li>
   <li><strong>1932</strong> At the age of 12 he wrote his own sequel to The Warlord of Mars</li>
   <li><strong>1932</strong> At age twelve, began writing traditional horror stories and said he tried to imitate Edgar Allan Poe until he was eighteen</li>
  <li><strong>1934</strong> Bradbury's first pay as a writer was at the age of fourteen, when Burns hired him to write for the Burns and Allen show</li>
  <li><strong>1934</strong> When Bradbury was 14 the family eventually settled in Los Angeles</li>
  <li><strong>1934</strong> When he moved to Los Angeles he attended high school and was active in the drama club</li>
  <li><strong>January 1938</strong> First published story was "Hollerbochen's Dilemma" which appeared in the fanzine.</li>
  <li><strong>1942</strong> Sold newspapers from high school graduation</li>
  <li><strong>1946</strong> Bradbury's first story about the Addams family was "Homecoming" published in the Halloween issue of Mademoiselle</li>
   <li><strong>1947</strong> His first collection, Dark Carnival, was published</li>
  <li><strong>1947</strong> He married Maggie McClure</li>
  <li><strong>1950</strong> The Martian Chronicles was published</li> <li><strong>1953</strong> His first science fiction book Fahrenheit 451 was published
</li>
  <li><strong>1954</strong> He was given the Benjamin Franklin Award</li>
  <li><strong>1999</strong> Bradbury suffered a stoke that left him partially dependent on a wheelchair for mobility.</li>
    <li><strong>2000</strong> He was awarded National Book Foundation Medal for Distinguished Contribution to American Letters</li>
  <li><strong>October 2001</strong> Bradbury published all the Family stories he had written in one book with a collecting narrative</li>
  <li><strong>2006</strong> Bradbury published the original novel remaining after the extraction, and re titled it "Farewell Summer"</li>
  <li><strong>June 5, 2012</strong> Bradbury died in Los Angeles, California, at the age of 91, after a lengthy illness. </li>
</ul></div>
<div class="coral-background"> <blockquote>
           <h4>“You don't have to burn books to destroy a culture. Just get people to stop reading them.”</h4>
            <footer><cite>Ray Bradbury</cite></footer>
          </blockquote></div>

<p>If you have time, you should read more about this incredible human being on his  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Bradbury">Wikipedia entry.</a></p></div>
